TY  - JOUR
AU  - Bianchi, Javier
AU  - Mondragon, Jorge
T1  - Monetary Independence and Rollover Crises*
PY  - 2022
Y1  - 2022/02/01
DO  - 10.1093/qje/qjab025
JO  - The Quarterly Journal of Economics
JA  - Q J Econ
VL  - 137
IS  - 1
SP  - 435
EP  - 491
SN  - 0033-5533
AB  - This article shows that the inability to use monetary policy for macroeconomic stabilization leaves a government more vulnerable to a rollover crisis. We study a sovereign default model with self-fulfilling rollover crises, foreign currency debt, and nominal rigidities. When the government lacks monetary independence, lenders anticipate that the government would face a severe recession in the event of a liquidity crisis and are therefore more prone to run on government bonds. In a quantitative application to the Eurozone debt crisis, we find that the lack of monetary autonomy played a central role in making Spain vulnerable to a rollover crisis. Finally, we argue that a lender of last resort can go a long way toward reducing the costs of giving up monetary independence.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/qje/qjab025
ER  - 



