TY  - JOUR
AU  - vom Lehn, Christian
AU  - Winberry, Thomas
T1  - The Investment Network, Sectoral Comovement, and the Changing U.S. Business Cycle*
PY  - 2022
Y1  - 2022/02/01
DO  - 10.1093/qje/qjab020
JO  - The Quarterly Journal of Economics
JA  - Q J Econ
VL  - 137
IS  - 1
SP  - 387
EP  - 433
SN  - 0033-5533
AB  - We argue that the network of investment production and purchases across sectors is an important propagation mechanism for understanding business cycles. Empirically, we show that the majority of investment goods are produced by a few “investment hubs,” which are more cyclical than other sectors. We embed this investment network into a multisector business cycle model and show that sector-specific shocks to the investment hubs and their key suppliers have large effects on aggregate employment and drive down labor productivity. Quantitatively, we find that sector-specific shocks to hubs and their suppliers account for an increasing share of aggregate fluctuations over time, generating the declining cyclicality of labor productivity and other changes in business cycle patterns since the 1980s.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/qje/qjab020
ER  - 



